{"/service/ndnp/msar/batch_msar_gabardine_ver01/data/sn87065163/00199916804/1908032701/0152.xml":{"full_text":"rotter and Collins\nAllowed Bail at $500\nThe cases of John Trotter and\nKey Collins, charged with manufactur\ning or passing of counterfeit coin In\nHattiesburg were called before the\nfederal commissioner In Biloxi Wed\nnesday and the following account of\nthe same Is given in a Biloxi special\nto the Gulfport Record-Tribune:\nKey Collins and John Trotter, the\ntwo negroes charged with being im\nplicated m the manufacture of count\nerfeit coin at Hattiesburg, were yes\nterday brought up from Gulfport by\nU. S. Marslml C. C. Buckley and\nhaled before U. S. Commissioner Roy\nChinn. Both negroes waived prelim\ninary examination by agreement be\ntween TJ. S. Attorney Lee and the at\ntorhey for the defendants, their bonds\nbeing reduced from 1,000 to $500.\nThe two men were taken back to\nGulfport and placed in jail, but it is\nSOME GOOD VALUES\nSPECIAL BARGAINS\nI N\nUNION-MADE OVERALLS\nWORKMAN'S GLOVES\n$1\n$1.50 Gloves\nLegular price $1.00\ngoing at_\n75c\ngoing at\nNew Spring Shoes Have Arrived\nLatest shades in Tans, Browns, Blacks in Patent Kid,\nChrome Patent and Vici Kid.\nHALfi HOSE in Lisle and Cotton, Newest Colors.\nEVERYTHING IN GENT'S FURNISINGS.\nAnd at Prices that are Real Bargains.\nJ. W. POOL,\nOpp. Hotel Hattiesburg\nobile St.\nNOTICE\nr\no Our Customers!\n1\nWe have moved our grocery business just across the street,\nrst door north of Thompson's Sale Stable, East Pine street,\niliere we will be pleased to serve you as heretofore.\nYou are cordially invited to make our store your headquarters\n|e will make it to your interest in prices and quality.\n'i\nFresh\njjwjf'getables and fruit received dally. Prompt delivery to all parts\nfcsEE\nI the city. 'Phone us your wants. Home 'Phone 145; Cumber\nVery respectfully,\n,nd 246.\nMoore Bros. Grocery Co.\nOPEN AN ACCOUNT IN OUR SAVINGS DEPARTMENT,\nINTEREST PAID ON BALANCES.\nn\n42 'PQsitary\nS\u00a3c </R/ry\n\u25a00 6\nFOR\nCOUNTY, and\n\n_ _ _ '-V_____\n*B/c, rr Or STOCKHOLDERS (as f> r d,dk LA\nTo DEPOSITORS\n*Or.\nAl\nWE SOLICIT\nACCOUNTS\n-I\nKAMP ER, v/ct PKtsT.\nfT*cnv\u00a3 viccpMtr /I'.L.f/At/iNDfi/fycAsZtt?\nJeJ. J. HAUENSTE/N, ASircAsmett.\n\u2022SP CARTER,\nEWfOO\nV\nyn\u00a3i?.>.\nif\n\u2022r>rr pma.\ni.\nexpected that they will be able to\nmake bond within a few days at the\nmost. Their cases will come up for\ntrial at the August term of federal\ncourt.\nCLAIM 148 DELEGATES.\nTaft Men Show That They Have a\nHeavy Lead.\nWashington, March 26.\u2014Secretary\nTaft today has 148 uncontested and\ninstructed delegates, according to his\nmanagers. They claim 174 votes, but\n26 of those instructed for him are\ncontested.\nUp to this time a total of 220 dele\ngates have been chosen. Twelve dele\ngates are uninstructed. Of the 34 dble\ngates instructed for other candidates\nthan Taft-26 are for Fairbanks and\n8 for Cannon.\nSTEP TOWARD\nPROSPERITY\nReopening of Knickerbocker Trust\nCompany Has Excellent\nEffect in New York,\nRECEIVERS ARE DISMISSED\nAND OFFICERS TAKE CHARGE\nDepositors Cannot Withdraw All of\nTheir Funds, But Will Ultimately\nBe Paid in Full\u2014Whole Country is\n.Benefitted.\nAssociated Press.\nNew York, March 26.\u2014Marking an\nother decided step toward the return\nof prosperity to the metropolis, the\nKnickerbocker Trust Company, which\nclosed its doors last October, was re\nopened for business at noon today.\nThe bank has assets of over $50,000,\n000, with liabilities slightly less, and\nthere is every likelihood it will be\nable to pay all of the 20,000 depos\nitors in full.\nThe reopening of the Knickerbock\ner Trust Company, in accordance with\nplans for its rehabilitation, prepared\nafter four months' labor by a commit\ntee of depositors, released to the\ncommunity assets aggregating $46,\n370,620.\n\"The reopening of the Knicker\nbocker Trust Company,\" declared\nJames Russell Seely, of the counsel\nfor the depositors' committee, \"will\nhave a stimulating effect not only\nupon the local financial situation, but\nupon every financial center on the\nglobe. It is the best thing that has\nhappened since the panic.\"\nJustice Clarke, in dismissing the\ntemporary receivers of the suspend\ned trust company and signing the re\nsumption order, spoke in commenda\ntory vein of the work of the deposi\ntors' committee, counsel and others\nwho had labored so assiduously in\nworking out the rehabilitation plan.\nUnder the terms of this plan the de\npositors of the Knickerbocker Trust\nCompany will not receive their de\nposits in full when the trust com\npany opens its doors, but will receive\n10 per cent, today if they want it and\nthe remaining portions of the deposits\ncan be withdrawn at intervals cover\ning a period of about two and one\nhalf years.\n44444444\nVALUE OF NEWSPAPER\nOVER THE HANDBILL. 4\nA newspaper has 5,000 read- 4\ners for each 1.000 subscribers. 4\nA merchant who puts out 1,000 4\nhandbills gets possibly 300 or 4\n400 people to read\u2014that is, If 4\nthe boy who is trusted to distrlb- 4\nute them does not chuck them 4\n4 under the sidewalk. The hand- 4\nbill costs as much as a half <8\u00bb\ncolumn advertisement In the 4\nhome paper. All the 'women and 4\ngirls and half the men and boys 4\nread the advertisements.\nsuit: The merchant who uses 4\nthe newspaper has 3,500 more 4\nreaders to each 1000 of paper's\nreaders. There Is no estimating 4\nthe amount of business that ad- 4\nvertising does bring to a mer-\nchant, but each dollar brings\nsomewhere from $20 to $100 4\n4 worth of business.\u2014Albon, Mich. 4\n4 Evening Recorder.\n0004 064404 4\n\n4\nRe- 6\ntr\n\\\\w\nIMfi\nA\nT*J53\u00bb\nThose Awful Headaches\nin ninety-nine cases out of a\nhundred are the results of eye\nstrain, We have countless\ncases where people have neg\nlected to have their eyes cared\nfor and fitted with glasses at\nthe proper time, and that we\nhave relieved entirely by test\ning their sight by our scientific\nmethods and fitting it with\nproperly adjusted eyeglasses\nor spectacles.\nF. W. QUEEN, Oph. D.\nOptical Specialist,\nCarter building.\nSecond floor.\nTRAIN TO NATCHEZ\nEARLY IN AUGUST\nTRACKLAYING WILL SOON BEGIN\nON LAST STRETCH.\nMuch Heavy Work Remains to Be\nDone Between Natchez and Rcxie\u2014\nSteam 8hovel, Will Be Used\u2014Ma\nterial is Hard to Get.\nDaily News Special.\nNatchez, March 26.\u2014The Gibson\ncontract for tracklaying on the Missis\nsippi Central railroad between Natchez\nand Morgan's Fork, six miles beyond\nRoxie, a total distance of 30 miles,\nwill be completed within the next\ntwo weeks and turned over to the\nUnited States Construction company.\n\"This will leave a gap of abuet\neight miles between Morgan's Fork\nand the Homochitto river on which\nthe grading has not been completed.\nConstruction trains are running be\ntween this city and a point near Mor\ngan's Fork, but it will be as late as\nJuly or August before through serv\nice is established between Natchez\nand Hattiesburg.\nMuch heavy work remains to be\ndone between Natchez and Roxie be\nfore train service can be establish\ned. At Bailey's cut. 11 miles on*,\nand at Shackelford's cut, 20 miles\nout, a large amount of earth is yet\nto be removed, and this work will\nnecessitate the operaUon of steam\nshovels. It Is possible for trains to\npass through these cuts now, but the\nwork will have to be done before a\nsafe service can be instituted.\nThe contractors having charge of\nthe tracklaying have been confront\ned with many difficulties. The winter\nhas been an unusually hard one, an 1\nthe work has been handicapped by\nweather conditions. Not only th's.\nbut there has been great difficulty in\nsecuring material for the work. Much\nof the delay has been due to the\nfact that ties and steel were not fur-'\nnished promptly.\nCLOTHING TALK\nBY POPULAR FIRM\nThe progressive and wide awake\nfirm of J. S.\nsomething Interesting to say to the\nreaders of the Daily News in their\nadvertisement this morning.\nWhen it comes to handling and sell\ning high-class goods, this firm always\nhas some extrarodlnary to offer. Read\ntheir attractive announcement.\nTurner Co., have\n444444446444444444\nThe Daily Newa now reaches\n1,800 homes in the Hattiesburg 4\ndistrict It has more than 1,200 4\n4 subscribers In the city alone. 4\nWe believe that this Is more than\ncan be said of any other news- 4\n4 paper in South Mississippi.\n4 We want you to come and see 4\n4 the list, count the names If you 4\n4 like.\n4\n4\n4 Sou can talk to more people, 4\n4 for less money, through the col-\ne-Dally News than 4\n4 through any othePn\u00bbtf?WB\u00abw.\n4444444444 4.4 444\n4\n\nWINGATE MAHERS\nOF MUCH MOMENT\nWingate, Miss., March 26.\u2014Mr. E.\nSmall has completed the repair work\non his store building and a nice struc\nture Is the result.\nSince Will Rosebrock met his death\ntrying to steal chickens many of the\n\"dirty dozen\" have shaken the dust\nfrom their sandals for newer fields\nand pastures green.\nA birthday party In honor of Miss\nJannie Newburn Is announced for to\nnight.\nMrs. Geo. Dennis departed for\nRlchton today where she will make\nher future home.\nC. C. Clark has received his blanks\nfor enumerating educable children\nand is again on his assessing tour.\nDr. B. T. Robinson was In Wingate\nyesterday.\nH. P. Smith was here yesterday\nfrom New Augusta.\nMrs. Davis Is sick this week.\nDan Nichols Is sick.\nSection Foreman Dorsey has a sick\nchild In his family this week.\nH. S. Brown, station agent, has\ngone Into the chicken business.\nByrd Buckwalter has returned from\nHattiesburg, where he went on busi\nDo Not Crowd the Season.\nThe first warm days of spring brln\nwith them a desire to get out and en\nJoy the exhilirating air and sunshine\nChildren that have been housed\nall winter are brought out and you\nwonder where they all came from\nThe heavy winter clothing Is thrown\naside and many shed their flannels\nThen a cold wave comes and people\nsay that grip is epidemic. Colds at\nthis season are even more dangerous\nthan in mid-winter, as there Is much\nmore danger of pneumonia,\nChamberlain's Cough Remedy, how\never, and you will have nothing to\nfear. It always cures, and we have\nnever known a cold to result In pneu\nmonia when It was used. It Is plea\nsant and safe to take. Children like it\nFor sale by Hays Field and Yellow\nPine Pharmacy.\nup\nTake\nAguila.\nAgulta.\nThe best 5c Cigar.\nLOVE DRUG CO.\nm12\nHave your furniture overhauled and\nmade to look good as new. Home\n'phone 551. m24-3t\nRAMSEY CO.\nUNDERTAKERS\nMUNICIPAL ANNOUNCEMENTS\nThe Dally News is authorised to an\nnounce the following candidates sub\nject to the action of the voters of the\ncity of Hattiesburg:\nFOR MAYOR.\nDR. E. DILL.\nDR. J. *D. DONALD.\nC. W. RICH.\nFOR POLICE JUSTICE.\nE. A. ANDERSON.\nC. F. REDDOCH.\nFOR CITY CLERK.\nA. FAIRLEY.\nFOR ALDERMEN.\n(Ward One.)\nF. H. CLINE.\nM. J. EPLEY.\nJ. A. FRAZIER.\n(Ward Two.)\nH. C. GREER.\nJ. W. GAY.\n(Ward Three.\nJOHN F. ANDERSON.\nM. DUNN.\nA. T. POWE.\nJ. S. DEES.\n(Ward Four.)\nHERMAN KATZ.\nR. C. McKENZIE.\nT. O. WATKINS.\nT. A. HIGHTOWER.\nALDERMAN-AT-LARGE.\nm. j. McGrath.\nFOR CITY TREASURER.\nE. B. GEORGE.\nJOHN WILLIAMS.\nFOR CHIEF OF POLICE.\nCHARLES POOLE.\nJ. F. WILMHB.\nrtrfft\nA'*,', \"iisSa\nmm\n\nHATTIESBURG TRUST\nANI>\n\n\nBANKING COMPANY\n\nCapital $150,000.00\nUndivided Profits'$12,000.00\nGeneral banking business transacted. Authorized by\nlaw to act as Administrator of Estates, Executor un\nder Wills, Guardian of Minors, Trustee, Assignee or\nReceiver.\nCAREFUL ATTENTION To All SUCH\nMATTERS ENTRUSTED TO US\nWe pay 4 per cent interest on Savings Deposits.\nCompounded Semi-Annually.\nTime Deposits.\n4 per cent on\nOFFICERS\nH. A. Camp,\nJoe Shelby, Vice Pres.\nPresident\nR. L. Bennett, dCashier\nJohn Kamper Vice\nR. B. McLeod, Asst.,\nLET US FIGURE WITH YOU\nON YOUR BILL OF LUMBER\n\n/X\nWe are headquarters for all kinds of\nbuilder's supplies a